04753nam a22005895i 9780822386421DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223864217 a10.1515/97808223864212doi  a(DE-B1597)554595  a(OCoLC)1170100163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGE170b.A26 2005 7aBUS0720002bisacsh04a333.721 aAgrawal, Arun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnvironmentality :bTechnologies of Government and the Making of Subjects /cArun Agrawal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b3 photos, 17 tables, 3 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Ecologies for the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The Politics of Nature and the Making of Environmental Subjects -- tPart I Power/Knowledge and the Creation of Forests -- t2. Forests of Statistics: Colonial Environmental Knowledges -- t3. Struggles over Kumaon's Forests, 1815-1916 -- tPart II. A New Technology of Environmental Government: Politics, Institutions, and Subjectivities -- t4. Governmentalized Localities: The Dispersal of Regulation -- t5. Inside the Regulatory Community -- t6. Making Environmental Subjects: Intimate Government -- t7. Conclusion: The Analytics of Environmentality -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Kumaon in northern India, villagers set hundreds of forest fires in the early 1920s, protesting the colonial British state's regulations to protect the environment. Yet by the 1990s, they had begun to conserve their forests carefully. In his innovative historical and political study, Arun Agrawal analyzes this striking transformation. He describes and explains the emergence of environmental identities and changes in state-locality relations and shows how the two are related. In so doing, he demonstrates that scholarship on common property, political ecology, and feminist environmentalism can be combined-in an approach he calls environmentality-to better understand changes in conservation efforts. Such an understanding is relevant far beyond Kumaon: local populations in more than fifty countries are engaged in similar efforts to protect their environmental resources.Agrawal brings environment and development studies, new institutional economics, and Foucauldian theories of power and subjectivity to bear on his ethnographical and historical research. He visited nearly forty villages in Kumaon, where he assessed the state of village forests, interviewed hundreds of Kumaonis, and examined local records. Drawing on his extensive fieldwork and archival research, he shows how decentralization strategies change relations between states and localities, community decision makers and common residents, and individuals and the environment. In exploring these changes and their significance, Agrawal establishes that theories of environmental politics are enriched by attention to the interconnections between power, knowledge, institutions, and subjectivities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aEnvironmental managementxDecision making. 0aEnvironmental managementzIndia. 0aEnvironmental policyxDecision making. 0aEnvironmental policyzIndia. 0aForest conservationzKumaun Himalaya. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386421zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter